'''Ted Chiang''' (born 1967) is an American [[science fiction]] writer. His Chinese name is Chiang Feng-nan (姜峯楠).

His work has won four [[Nebula Award|Nebula awards]], four [[Hugo Award|Hugo awards]], the [[John W. Campbell Award for Best New Writer]], and four [[Locus Award|Locus awards]].<ref>[http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/eaw.cgi?11251 Chiang's awards] at ISFDB</ref> His short story "[[Story of Your Life]]" was adapted to a film called ''[[Arrival_(film)|Arrival]]'' in 2016.

==Early life and career==
Chiang was born in [[Port Jefferson, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?Ted_Chiang |title = Ted Chiang – Summary Bibliography |publisher = The Internet Speculative Fction Database |accessdate = October 4, 2012 }}</ref> Both of his parents were born in [[China]], but immigrated to [[Taiwan]] with their families during the [[Chinese Communist Revolution|Communist Revolution]] before immigrating to the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/persons-of-interest/ted-chiangs-soulful-science-fiction |title=Ted Chiang's Soulful Science Fiction |last=Rothman |first=Joshua |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=January 5, 2017 |accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref> He graduated from [[Brown University]] with a [[computer science]] degree and in 1989 graduated from the [[Clarion Workshop|Clarion Writers Workshop]]. He currently works as a [[technical writer]] in the software industry and resides in [[Bellevue, Washington]], near [[Seattle]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.sfsite.com/09b/tc136.htm |title = An Interview with Ted Chiang |publisher = SF Site |accessdate = October 4, 2012 }}</ref>  

Critic [[John Clute]] has written that Chiang's writing has a "tight-hewn and lucid style ... [which] has a magnetic effect on the reader."<ref>[http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/chiang_ted Chiang's entry at SF Encyclopedia]</ref>

==Awards==
Chiang has published fifteen short stories, novelettes, and novellas {{as of|2015|lc=y}}, and has won numerous science fiction awards for his works: a [[Nebula Award]] for "[[Tower of Babylon (story)|Tower of Babylon]]" (1990); the [[John W. Campbell Award for Best New Writer]] in 1992; a [[Nebula Award]] and the [[Theodore Sturgeon Award]] for "[[Story of Your Life]]" (1998); a [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History|Sidewise Award]] for "Seventy-Two Letters" (2000); a Nebula Award, [[Locus Award]], and [[Hugo Award]] for his [[Novella|novelette]] "[[Hell Is the Absence of God]]" (2002); a Nebula and Hugo Award for his novelette "[[The Merchant and the Alchemist's Gate]]" (2007); a British Science Fiction Association Award, a [[Locus Award]], and the [[Hugo Award for Best Short Story]] for "[[Exhalation (short story)|Exhalation]]" (2009); and a Hugo Award<ref>{{cite news|work=Locus|url=http://www.locusmag.com/News/2011/08/2011-hugo-and-campbell-awards-winners/ |title=2011 Hugo and Campbell Awards Winners|accessdate =August 21, 2011}}</ref> and Locus Award for his novella "[[The Lifecycle of Software Objects]]" (2010).

Chiang turned down a Hugo nomination for his short story "Liking What You See: A Documentary" in 2003, on the grounds that the story was rushed due to editorial pressure and did not turn out as he had really wanted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fantasticmetropolis.com/i/chiang/full/ |website=fantasticmetropolis.com|title=Chiang}}</ref>

In 2013, his collection of translated stories ''Die Hölle ist die Abwesenheit Gottes'' won the German [[Kurd-Laßwitz-Preis]] for best foreign science fiction.

